properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility occasionally near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A frontal system moving across northern Yukon will produce blizzard conditions over the Dempster region this evening. The blizzard will end tonight as the system weakens. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions near White Pass tonight. Most of the South Klondike Highway will see periods of snow and blowing snow with the worst conditions expected to be by the border at White Pass. Visibilities in snow and blowing snow will be below 400 metres. Blizzard conditions will ease overnight. Local blowing snow will continue into Thursday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A low over the Gulf of Alaska moved into Yukon earlier this afternoon. In the wake of the low, southwesterly winds gusting to 90 km/h are possible in Haines Junction early this evening. Winds will ease late this evening as the low moves away. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Periods of intense snowfall with blowing snow this morning. Total snowfall: 5 to 15 cm, with locally higher amounts possible. Wind gusts: up to 70 km/h Locations: Cape Breton Island and eastern Mainland Nova Scotia. Time span: early this morning. Remarks: A short period of heavy snow accompanied by strong northerly winds and blowing snow will continue for a few more hours over eastern Nova Scotia. Heavy snowfall rates of several centimetres per hour and blowing snow will combine to give poor visibilities at times. Conditions will improve later morning as the system responsible moves offshore. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. As of 9:20 pm weather radar is showing a band of freezing rain currently in eastern Alberta approaching the Saskatchewan border. The freezing rain should begin at the border late this evening, and will likely last for an hour or so. Current indications are that the freezing rain will peter our before it reaches the Battlefords, however areas west of there including Maidstone, Kerrobert, Unity and Kindersley will likely experience some freezing precipitation through the overnight hours. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. As of 11:20 pm weather radar is showing a band of freezing rain which has now moved into western Saskatchewan. Many areas under the freezing rain warning can expect an hour or so of freezing rain during the overnight hours. The band of freezing rain is not continuous, so some areas will see little if any precipitation. Temperatures are also rising above the freezing mark in the southwest corner of the province, so these areas will see rain and not freezing rain. The freezing rain should peter out towards morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High concentration of pollutants are expected and will result in poor air quality, especially in urban areas where pollutant emissions are higher. High concentrations of pollutants are expected to persist through Thursday morning. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. In Quebec, wood heating is the main source of fine particles that contribute to smog during winter. This activity generates the largest number of these particulates, more than industrial activities and transportation. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canadas website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministre de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montral, visit the Rseau de surveillance de la qualit de lair de la Ville de Montrals website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Qubec, visit the Ministre de la Sant et des Services sociauxs website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction rgionale de sant publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-lle-de-Montral at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
